\begin_layout Standard
As control input, an onramp 
\begin_inset Formula $2\link-1\in\links,\link\in\intrange 1{\nlinks}$
\end_inset

 at time-step 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\intrange 0{\ntime-1}$
\end_inset

 has a metering rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\ramp_{2\link-1}^{\tind}\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 which limits the flux of vehicles leaving the onramp.
 Intuitively, the metering rate acts as a fractional decrease in the flow
 leaving the onramp and entering the mainline freeway.
 The bounded domain of the metering control is to force the control to neither
 impose negative flows nor send more vehicles than present in a queue.
 Its mathematical model is expressed in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ramp-eqn"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For notational simplicity we define the set of densities of links adjacent
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\jup{2\link}=\jdown{2\left(\link-1\right)}$
\end_inset

 at time-step 
\begin_inset Formula $\tind$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\juncstate{\jup{2\link}}{\tind}=\left\{ \discrete{2\left(\link-1\right)}{\tind},\discrete{2i-1}{\tind},\discrete{2\link}{\tind}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The offramp is considered to have infinite capacity, and thus has no bearing
 on the solution of junction problems.
 Initial conditions are handled as in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:init-ge"

\end_inset

, while for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\intrange 1{\ntime-1}$
\end_inset

, the mainline density 
\begin_inset Formula $\discrete{2\link}{\tind}$
\end_inset

 using the Godunov scheme from
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:main-ge"

\end_inset

 is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\syseq_{2\link}^{\tind}(\state,\control) & =\discrete{2\link}{\tind}-\discrete{2\link}{\tind-1} & +\dfrac{\Delta t}{\length_{\link}}\left(\god_{\jdown{2\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jdown{2\link}}{\tind-1},\ramp_{2\link+1}^{\tind-1}\right)\right)_{2\link}\label{eq:rho-update}\\
 &  & -\dfrac{\Delta t}{\length_{\link}}\left(\god_{\jup{2\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jup{2\link}}{\tind-1},\ramp_{2\link-1}^{\tind-1}\right)\right)_{2\link}\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\length_{\link}$
\end_inset

 is the length of link 
\begin_inset Formula $2\link\in\links$
\end_inset

.
 We also make the assumption that onramps have infinite capacity and a free-flow
 velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\ffspeed_{2\link-1}=\frac{\length_{2\link-1}}{\Delta t}$
\end_inset

 to prevent the ramp congestion from blocking demand from ever entering
 the network.
 Since the onramp is has no physical length, the length is chosen arbitrarily
 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

virtual
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 velocity chosen above is chosen to replicate the dynamics in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Monache2013"

\end_inset

.
 We can then simplify the onramp update equation to be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\syseq_{2\link-1}^{\tind}(\state,\control)=\discrete{2\link-1}{\tind}-\discrete{2\link-1}{\tind-1}+\frac{\Delta t}{\length_{\link}}\left(\left(\god_{\jup{2\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jup{2\link}}{\tind-1},\ramp_{2\link-1}^{\tind-1}\right)\right)_{2\link-1}-\boundaryDemand{2\link-1}{\tind}\right)=0\label{eq:onramp-update}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boundaryDemand{2\link-1}{\tind}$
\end_inset

 is the onramp 
\emph on
flux 
\emph default
demand, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\link\in\intrange 1{\nlinks}$
\end_inset

.
 This formulation results in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

strong
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 boundary conditions at the onramps which guarantees all demand enters the
 network.
 Details on weak versus strong boundary conditions can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Monache2013,Walid,strub2006weak,work2010traffic"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

