\begin_layout Paragraph
Riemann solver.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the ramp metering problem, there are many potential Riemann solvers
 that satisfy the properties required in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Network-of-PDE's"

\end_inset

.
 Following the model of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Walid,ML"

\end_inset

, for each junction 
\begin_inset Formula $\jup{2\link}$
\end_inset

, we add two modeling decisions: the flux solution maximizes the outgoing
 mainline flux 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\god_{\jup{2\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jup{2\link}}{\tind},\ramp_{2\link-1}^{\tind}\right)\right)_{2\link}$
\end_inset

, and any remaining non-uniqueness in the incoming flux is resolved using
 a merging parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2(\link-1)}\in\mathbb{R}_{+}$
\end_inset

, which models the manner in which vehicles merge from two roads to one,
 shown in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:merge"

\end_inset

.
 This leads to the following system of equations that gives the flux solution
 of the Riemann solver at time-step 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\intrange 1{\ntime-1}$
\end_inset

 and junction 
\begin_inset Formula $\jup{2\link}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\link\in\intrange 1{\nlinks}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\demand_{2\left(\link-1\right)}^{\tind} & = & \min\left(\ffspeed_{2\left(i-1\right)}\densitydiscrete{2\left(\link-1\right)}{\tind},F_{2\left(\link-1\right)}^{\max}\right)\label{eq:first-ramp}\\
\supply_{2\link}^{\tind} & = & \min\left(\congspeed_{2i}\left(\density_{2i}^{\max}-\densitydiscrete{2\link}{\tind}\right),F_{2i}^{\max}\right)\label{eq:supply}\\
\rampDemand_{2\link-1}^{\tind} & = & \ramp_{2\link-1}^{\tind}\min\left(\frac{\length_{2\link-1}}{\Delta t}\densitydiscrete{2\link-1}{\tind},F_{2i-1}^{\max}\right)\label{eq:ramp-eqn}\\
\left(\god_{\jup{2\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jup{2\link}}{\tind},\ramp_{2\link-1}^{\tind}\right)\right)_{2\link} & = & \min\left(\splitratio_{2\left(\link-1\right)}^{\tind}\demand_{2\left(\link-1\right)}^{\tind}+\rampDemand_{2\link-1}^{\tind},\supply_{2\link}^{\tind}\right)\label{eq:fin}\\
\left(\god_{\jup{2\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jup{2\link}}{\tind},\ramp_{2\link-1}^{\tind}\right)\right)_{2\left(\link-1\right)} & = & \begin{cases}
\demand_{2\left(\link-1\right)}^{\tind} & \frac{p_{2(\link-1)}\left(\god_{\jup{2\link}}\right)_{2\link}}{\splitratio_{2\left(\link-1\right)}^{\tind}\left(1+p_{2(\link-1)}\right)}\ge\demand_{2\left(\link-1\right)}^{\tind}\hfill\text{[Case 1]}\\
\frac{\left(\god_{\jup{2\link}}\right)_{2\link}-\rampDemand_{2\link-1}^{\tind}}{\splitratio_{2\left(\link-1\right)}^{\tind}} & \frac{\left(\god_{\jup{2\link}}\right)_{2\link}}{1+p_{2(\link-1)}}\ge\rampDemand_{2\link-1}^{\tind}\hfill\text{[Case 2}]\\
\frac{p_{2(\link-1)}\left(\god_{\jup{2\link}}\right)_{2\link}}{\left(1+p_{2(\link-1)}\right)\splitratio_{2\left(\link-1\right)}^{\tind}} & \text{otherwise}\hfill[\text{Case 3]}
\end{cases}\label{eq:merge}\\
\left(\god_{\jup{2\link}}\left(\juncstate{\jup{2\link}}{\tind},\ramp_{2\link-1}^{\tind}\right)\right)_{2\link-1} & = & \left(\god_{\jup{2\link}}\right)_{2\link}-\splitratio_{2\left(\link-1\right)}^{\tind}\left(\god_{\jup{2\link}}\right)_{2\left(\link-1\right)}\label{eq:last-ramp}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where, for notational simplicity, at the edges of of the range for 
\begin_inset Formula $\link$
\end_inset

, any undefined state values (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\densitydiscrete 0{\tind}$
\end_inset

) are assumed to be zero.
 Equations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:first-ramp"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ramp-eqn"

\end_inset

 determine the maximum flux that can exit link 
\begin_inset Formula $2(\link-1)$
\end_inset

 and link 
\begin_inset Formula $2\link-1$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:supply"

\end_inset

 gives the maximum flux allowed into link 
\begin_inset Formula $2\link$
\end_inset

.
 The actual flux into link 
\begin_inset Formula $2\link$
\end_inset

, shown in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:fin"

\end_inset

, is given as the minimum of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

demand
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from upstream links and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

supply
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the downstream link.
 See
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Monache2013"

\end_inset

 for more details on the model for this equation.
 The flux out of link 
\begin_inset Formula $2(\link-1)$
\end_inset

 is split into three cases in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:merge"

\end_inset

.
 The solutions are depicted in Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Godunov-junction-flux"

\end_inset

, which demonstrates how the flux solution depends upon the relative demands
 and the merging parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2\left(\link-1\right)}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:last-ramp"

\end_inset

 gives the flux out of the onramp 
\begin_inset Formula $2\link-1$
\end_inset

, which is the difference between the flux into link 
\begin_inset Formula $2\link$
\end_inset

 and the flux out of link 
\begin_inset Formula $2\left(\link-1\right)$
\end_inset

 the remains on the mainline.
